<tt>Thu Dec 19  1:51:32 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
February 11, 1970.  I had hitched a ride on a deuce-and-a-half headed for Saigon from my duty station at Bien Hoa.<br><br>
I was with my buddies Ed Gentry and William Peterson.  The truck had maybe ten drums on it that were unlabelled.<br><br>
One of the drums started leaking a bright orange liquid out of it.<br><br>
Funny fumes came from the spilled liquid. We banged on the cab and had the driver stop.  He just kicked the drum off the truck and off we went.<br><br>
Ed and Bill never made it home, they were killed when the NVA over-ran Bien Hoa during Tet '70.<br><br>
Now I have symptoms of Agent Orange poisoning.<br><br>
Why did the Army let its soldiers get exposed to that bright orange syruppy liquid.<br><br>
We should all get $ 200,000 tax-free for our service.<br><br>
Phill
